"<brief_description>The XREAL glasses&#39; RGB camera exposed as a Godot [code]CameraFeed[/code] (full colour, via the native C ABI).</brief_description>\n"
"<description>Add it to the [code]CameraServer[/code] and call [code]poll_frame()[/code] each frame to grab the latest frame; sample [code]get_y_texture()[/code] (R8 luma) and [code]get_cbcr_texture()[/code] (RG8 chroma) in a YCbCr→RGB shader to display it ([code]addons/godot_xreal/shaders/xreal_ycbcr*.gdshader[/code] do exactly that). Present only on glasses that carry an RGB camera (e.g. the One Pro, not the Air 2 Ultra — gate on [code]XrealSystem.is_camera_supported()[/code]).[br][br][b]Read frames via the custom getters, not [code]CameraTexture[/code].[/b] If you know Godot&#39;s [code]CameraFeed[/code] this is the surprise: frames do NOT flow through the standard [code]CameraServer[/code] texture route by default. On this build a [code]CameraTexture[/code] bound to a script-fed feed shows only the placeholder, so the addon bypasses it — [code]poll_frame()[/code] updates the two plain [code]ImageTexture[/code]s above and every consumer (camera panel, blend capture, stream, photo capture) samples those directly. Code that consumes feeds through the standard [code]CameraFeed[/code] API can opt in via [code]feed_camera_server[/code], which additionally pushes each frame into the base feed ([code]set_ycbcr_images[/code]) at the cost of a second per-frame GPU upload.</description>\n"
"<methods>\n"
"<method name=\"poll_frame\">\n"
"  <return type=\"bool\" />\n"
"  \n"
"  <description>\n"
"  Poll the latest RGB-camera frame and refresh [code]get_y_texture()[/code] / [code]get_cbcr_texture()[/code] (the textures the YCbCr→RGB shaders sample — the display route). With [code]feed_camera_server[/code] on it also pushes the frame into the base [code]CameraFeed[/code] as [b]separate Y + CbCr[/b] images ([code]FEED_YCBCR_SEP[/code]) for standard [code]CameraServer[/code] consumers. Returns [code]true[/code] if a frame was grabbed this call. Call once per frame from a driver.\n"
